What is T in Generics. What is significnce of ? in generics. why we use generics.
T in Generics is a type parameter that represents a generic type. It allows you to create classes, interfaces, and methods that can operate on any type of data. The significance of ? in generics is that it represents an unknown type. It is used when you want to specify that a method can accept any type of argument, but you don't care about the specific type. We use generics to provide type safety at compile time, to eliminate the need for casting, and to enable code reusability by allowing the same code to work with different types of data.
what is optimistic locking and pessimistic locking in java?
